00:02:28.300 --> 00:02:31.440
And there's been very little
conversation about the role

00:02:31.440 --> 00:02:34.170
that we all can play
in doing better.

00:02:34.170 --> 00:02:35.670
So I'm going to
back up for a second

00:02:35.670 --> 00:02:38.150
and just give you a little
bit about me and about why

00:02:38.150 --> 00:02:39.505
I wrote the book.

00:02:39.505 --> 00:02:41.380
Because I do think it's
important, especially

00:02:41.380 --> 00:02:45.300
because I am the white
privileged woman that I

00:02:45.300 --> 00:02:48.700
am, standing up here to talk
to a very diverse set of Google

00:02:48.700 --> 00:02:50.570
employees and out
there in the world

00:02:50.570 --> 00:02:52.760
talking to a very diverse
country about this topic.

00:02:52.760 --> 00:02:55.061
And so I do think and I
felt in writing the book

00:02:55.061 --> 00:02:57.060
that I needed to say a
little bit about who I am

00:02:57.060 --> 00:02:58.850
and how I got here.

00:02:58.850 --> 00:03:00.220
So I grew up in Washington DC.

00:03:00.220 --> 00:03:02.869
And Washington DC
has always been

00:03:02.869 --> 00:03:05.410
and remains and one of the most
diverse cities in the nation.

00:03:05.410 --> 00:03:08.130
In the 1980s, when I was
growing up, it was over 90%

00:03:08.130 --> 00:03:10.030
African-American.

00:03:10.030 --> 00:03:13.160
And my experience
of that childhood

00:03:13.160 --> 00:03:15.410
was-- I'm realizing
now and I've come

00:03:15.410 --> 00:03:17.480
to realize-- pretty unique.

00:03:17.480 --> 00:03:20.030
Because most American
don't grow up

00:03:20.030 --> 00:03:22.720
in communities that are anywhere
near as diverse as the one

00:03:22.720 --> 00:03:23.710
that I grew up in.

00:03:23.710 --> 00:03:27.170
Now, my immediate neighborhood,
the block where my house was,

00:03:27.170 --> 00:03:28.880
was actually almost
entirely white.

00:03:28.880 --> 00:03:30.886
And Washington is
actually segregated

00:03:30.886 --> 00:03:32.010
in these very strange ways.

00:03:32.010 --> 00:03:33.880
It's segregated by
race but it's also

00:03:33.880 --> 00:03:35.557
even segregated by
political party.

00:03:35.557 --> 00:03:37.390
We didn't have any
Republicans on our block.

00:03:37.390 --> 00:03:39.240
I mean, it was like
all Peace Corps,

00:03:39.240 --> 00:03:40.740
ex-Peace Peace Corps volunteers.

00:03:40.740 --> 00:03:44.010
So not the most of
our neighborhoods.

00:03:44.010 --> 00:03:45.840
But the city itself
was so diverse

00:03:45.840 --> 00:03:48.380
that all my schools
were incredibly diverse.

00:03:48.380 --> 00:03:50.787
I always had 30% to
40% of my classmates,

00:03:50.787 --> 00:03:52.870
from kindergarten all the
way through high school,

00:03:52.870 --> 00:03:54.870
and I write a lot about
high school in the book,

00:03:54.870 --> 00:03:58.820
were at leaves 30% to
40% diverse in some way,

00:03:58.820 --> 00:04:01.046
because this city is
also the home of all

00:04:01.046 --> 00:04:02.670
of the embassies for
the United States.

00:04:02.670 --> 00:04:05.330
And so there our families from
every corner of the world.

00:04:05.330 --> 00:04:08.150
In kindergarten, I probably had
nine different nationalities

00:04:08.150 --> 00:04:08.850
represented.

00:04:08.850 --> 00:04:11.750
And that left a
big impact on me.

00:04:11.750 --> 00:04:14.380
And I also had a lot of
African-American friends

00:04:14.380 --> 00:04:15.660
with a child.

00:04:15.660 --> 00:04:17.769
The thing that I came
to learn, though,

00:04:17.769 --> 00:04:20.149
and I really was, I
think like many kids,

00:04:20.149 --> 00:04:23.370
not especially conscious of
the thing that divided us

00:04:23.370 --> 00:04:28.240
as a child, but I was very lucky
because two things happened.

00:04:28.240 --> 00:04:30.740
One is that, in about
the seventh grade,

00:04:30.740 --> 00:04:33.400
and I write a lot about
this in the book--

00:04:33.400 --> 00:04:35.770
in the seventh grade, I
had this really painful

00:04:35.770 --> 00:04:38.990
personal experience,
which is that I was--

00:04:38.990 --> 00:04:40.946
and this is a very
seventh grade thing,

00:04:40.946 --> 00:04:42.570
to put it in context,
because we're all

00:04:42.570 --> 00:04:45.110
a little emotional
and a little awkward

00:04:45.110 --> 00:04:46.597
and sensitive in
the seventh grade.

00:04:46.597 --> 00:04:49.180
But in the seventh grade, I went
to this very exclusive girls'

00:04:49.180 --> 00:04:53.020
school, outside of DC, in
suburban Potomac, Maryland,

00:04:53.020 --> 00:04:56.105
which was very conservative,
entirely white.

00:04:56.105 --> 00:04:58.230
By the way, I stayed at
this school only two years,

00:04:58.230 --> 00:04:59.415
partly because of this.

00:04:59.415 --> 00:05:01.290
And in the seventh grade,
someone in my class

00:05:01.290 --> 00:05:03.350
had a birthday party,
and I was the only one

00:05:03.350 --> 00:05:05.300
in the class not invited.

00:05:05.300 --> 00:05:07.590
And it turns out that the
reason that I wasn't invited

00:05:07.590 --> 00:05:10.520
was because the party was being
held at the Chevy Chase Country

00:05:10.520 --> 00:05:15.120
Club, which in 1988, did
not have a single minority

00:05:15.120 --> 00:05:16.620
or Jewish member.

00:05:16.620 --> 00:05:19.910
Because we were Jewish,
I was not invited.

00:05:19.910 --> 00:05:23.990
My mom, when she explained to
me why I hadn't been invited,

00:05:23.990 --> 00:05:27.190
used it as an opportunity
to recount to me

00:05:27.190 --> 00:05:30.100
all the discrimination that
American Jews have faced.

00:05:30.100 --> 00:05:32.150
And it turns out that
my own grandfather

00:05:32.150 --> 00:05:34.870
had changed his
name in the 1950s ad

00:05:34.870 --> 00:05:37.970
from Goldberg to Gilbert,
because in most of America,

00:05:37.970 --> 00:05:40.640
he couldn't get a hotel room
with the last name Goldberg.

00:05:40.640 --> 00:05:43.580
It's a piece of American
history that most of us

00:05:43.580 --> 00:05:45.170
don't even think about anymore.

00:05:45.170 --> 00:05:48.010
But it was true.

00:05:48.010 --> 00:05:50.879
Was it the biggest,
most transformational

00:05:50.879 --> 00:05:52.170
personal experience in my life?

00:05:52.170 --> 00:05:52.960
Of course not.

00:05:52.960 --> 00:05:55.660
Does it compare in any way
to the kind of exclusion

00:05:55.660 --> 00:05:59.281
and challenges that visible
minorities in this country

00:05:59.281 --> 00:05:59.780
face?

00:05:59.780 --> 00:06:00.980
Of course not.

00:06:00.980 --> 00:06:04.640
But something happened for me
at that point in my life, which

00:06:04.640 --> 00:06:10.160
is that I was humiliated,
and angry, and hurt,

00:06:10.160 --> 00:06:13.060
and I could not stand
the injustice of it.

00:06:13.060 --> 00:06:14.910
It made me crazy.

00:06:14.910 --> 00:06:16.800
So to fast forward, I
was lucky enough to go.

00:06:16.800 --> 00:06:17.360
I left.

00:06:17.360 --> 00:06:19.240
I got out of that school
as soon as I could,

00:06:19.240 --> 00:06:20.560
and I went to a
school in Washington

00:06:20.560 --> 00:06:22.018
called Georgetown
Day School, which

00:06:22.018 --> 00:06:24.350
was actually built to
be the first integrated

00:06:24.350 --> 00:06:25.300
school in Washington.

00:06:25.300 --> 00:06:27.520
It was established in
the 1940s, at the time

00:06:27.520 --> 00:06:30.920
when DC was a highly segregated
city, which many people don't

00:06:30.920 --> 00:06:32.670
know the history of
Washington and how

00:06:32.670 --> 00:06:34.380
segregated it really was.

00:06:34.380 --> 00:06:38.110
But it was in many
ways a microcosm

00:06:38.110 --> 00:06:41.000
of the bias that was
happening in the nation.

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:45.420
But GDS was set up as this
place for diverse communities

00:06:45.420 --> 00:06:47.000
in Washington to get educated.

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:49.730
And so when I got there,
it also turned out

00:06:49.730 --> 00:06:52.460
to be a place where
people talked about race

00:06:52.460 --> 00:06:54.660
and difference all the time.

00:06:54.660 --> 00:06:56.660
And the school did
something really amazing,

00:06:56.660 --> 00:06:58.760
which is that in my
freshman year, when

00:06:58.760 --> 00:07:01.280
a bunch of African-American
senior girls

00:07:01.280 --> 00:07:04.240
were feeling angry
and like second class

00:07:04.240 --> 00:07:06.960
citizens in the school, because
they felt they were not being

00:07:06.960 --> 00:07:09.830
treated fairly by some of the
white students, the school,

00:07:09.830 --> 00:07:12.890
to their credit, suspended
classes for three days

00:07:12.890 --> 00:07:14.550
in my freshman year
of high school,

00:07:14.550 --> 00:07:18.260
and brought in Juan Williams,
who had not long before written

00:07:18.260 --> 00:07:22.050
the book "Eyes on the Prize,"
to facilitate a summit on race

00:07:22.050 --> 00:07:24.210
for a bunch of high school kids.

00:07:24.210 --> 00:07:25.376
It was life altering.

00:07:25.376 --> 00:07:27.610
But the thing about
that, and the reason

00:07:27.610 --> 00:07:29.940
why I tell that story,
is that part of what

00:07:29.940 --> 00:07:36.930
made me able to relate to and
understand, or at least try

00:07:36.930 --> 00:07:41.280
to understand, the pain that
these amazing African-American

00:07:41.280 --> 00:07:43.480
girls, who were seniors at
the time, who I worshiped

00:07:43.480 --> 00:07:45.780
and thought were the coolest
girls in the whole world,

00:07:45.780 --> 00:07:49.270
part of why I cried
for them was because I

00:07:49.270 --> 00:07:52.060
had had some experience
of being an outsider,

00:07:52.060 --> 00:07:54.480
that that experience of having
been excluded for something

00:07:54.480 --> 00:07:57.450
I couldn't control,
that I was Jewish,

00:07:57.450 --> 00:08:00.770
helped me understand something
different about them.

00:08:00.770 --> 00:08:02.230
So fast forward.

00:08:02.230 --> 00:08:04.780
Because I actually happen
to think-- first of all,

00:08:04.780 --> 00:08:06.610
I've come to realize
how lucky I am that I

00:08:06.610 --> 00:08:08.730
had any of those experiences.

00:08:08.730 --> 00:08:13.290
Because it has created--
and I am in no way

00:08:13.290 --> 00:08:15.550
left biased than anyone
else in the country.

00:08:15.550 --> 00:08:19.150
I am in no way-- I
don't understand it

00:08:19.150 --> 00:08:21.640
in any greater detail
than anybody else,

00:08:21.640 --> 00:08:25.020
but it has made me want to try.

00:08:25.020 --> 00:08:28.660
And it's made me commit a big
part of my career to trying

00:08:28.660 --> 00:08:31.080
to create the context
and the environment

00:08:31.080 --> 00:08:34.649
and the opportunities
for us all to do better.

00:08:34.649 --> 00:08:36.940
And that's what I committed
to when writing this book--

00:08:36.940 --> 00:08:39.074
could we find a
way to do better?

00:08:39.074 --> 00:08:41.240
Well, one thing that I think
is fundamental to that,

00:08:41.240 --> 00:08:45.310
and you can look at what's
happened in North Carolina

00:08:45.310 --> 00:08:47.770
or in Oklahoma or any
of the other places

00:08:47.770 --> 00:08:49.880
around the country now,
where there are now

00:08:49.880 --> 00:08:53.710
these endless streams of
hashtag that in a couple

00:08:53.710 --> 00:08:58.140
letters try to capture the pain
and the complexity of what's

00:08:58.140 --> 00:08:59.930
happening in the
country right now.

00:08:59.930 --> 00:09:04.000
We need desperately
for more Americans,

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:06.980
and I absolutely believe
that we especially need

00:09:06.980 --> 00:09:11.440
more white Americans, to have
a deeper appreciation for,

00:09:11.440 --> 00:09:17.320
empathy for, and understanding
of the experiences that

00:09:17.320 --> 00:09:20.260
non-majority-- although
even that is changing,

00:09:20.260 --> 00:09:22.720
so we'll talk about
that in a minute--

00:09:22.720 --> 00:09:25.200
how all Americans are
experiencing our country.

00:09:25.200 --> 00:09:28.480
If we cannot get to a
deeper level of empathy

00:09:28.480 --> 00:09:32.960
and understanding, we are doomed
to continue to repeat these

00:09:32.960 --> 00:09:36.680
same cycles over and over again.

00:09:36.680 --> 00:09:40.400
I do a lot of media, and I've
been spending a lot of time

00:09:40.400 --> 00:09:41.470
on Fox News.

00:09:41.470 --> 00:09:44.914
I've become the progressive
punching bag on Fox News.

00:09:44.914 --> 00:09:47.330
They love having me as often
as I'll come that day so they

00:09:47.330 --> 00:09:49.100
can scream and yell at me.

00:09:49.100 --> 00:09:53.300
But I was invited to speak
after one of the major incidents

00:09:53.300 --> 00:09:54.340
a few months ago.

00:09:54.340 --> 00:09:54.510
I can't even remember.

00:09:54.510 --> 00:09:55.660
Dallas, after Dallas.

00:09:55.660 --> 00:09:58.191
There have been so many
the year I lose track.

00:09:58.191 --> 00:09:59.690
But after the Dallas
shooting, I was

00:09:59.690 --> 00:10:03.230
invited on Megyn
Kelly's show to be part

00:10:03.230 --> 00:10:05.070
of this discussion on race.

00:10:05.070 --> 00:10:06.690
And I was kind of
optimistic about it.

00:10:06.690 --> 00:10:07.940
Because I thought, "all right.

00:10:07.940 --> 00:10:08.700
They're doing it.

00:10:08.700 --> 00:10:10.323
It's going to be
nationally televised.

00:10:10.323 --> 00:10:11.250
That's promising."

00:10:11.250 --> 00:10:13.540
And I get to the green
room and it's actually

00:10:13.540 --> 00:10:14.400
a very diverse room.

00:10:14.400 --> 00:10:16.862
And I'm kind of like,
"hm, well done, Fox News.

00:10:16.862 --> 00:10:18.330
I'm impressed with who
you've pulled into this room

00:10:18.330 --> 00:10:19.455
to have this conversation."

00:10:19.455 --> 00:10:21.505
And we go in, and we
sit down in the chairs

00:10:21.505 --> 00:10:22.630
before the cameras come on.

00:10:22.630 --> 00:10:24.590
And the producer
says, "we really need

00:10:24.590 --> 00:10:27.460
a thoughtful and meaningful
conversation about this.

00:10:27.460 --> 00:10:29.747
This is a time when the
country is in crisis.

00:10:29.747 --> 00:10:31.330
We want all of you
to bring your best.

00:10:31.330 --> 00:10:32.700
Please don't scream.

00:10:32.700 --> 00:10:34.120
People will change the channel.

00:10:34.120 --> 00:10:35.500
It's not good for
ratings, but it's also not

00:10:35.500 --> 00:10:36.380
good for this conversation."

00:10:36.380 --> 00:10:37.260
So I'm feeling great.

00:10:37.260 --> 00:10:38.240
I'm like, "yeah,
we're going to have

00:10:38.240 --> 00:10:39.820
this meaningful conversation.

00:10:39.820 --> 00:10:41.230
Yay, Fox News."

00:10:41.230 --> 00:10:44.950
I'm sure you can guess that
it didn't quite go that way.

00:10:44.950 --> 00:10:50.080
So it opened with one guest who
started with the following--

00:10:50.080 --> 00:10:54.467
"Black Lives Matter is
more racist than the KKK."

00:10:54.467 --> 00:10:55.300
That was the opener.

00:10:55.300 --> 00:10:57.482
So you can imagine where
it went from there.

00:10:57.482 --> 00:10:59.440
By the way, that was an
African-American person

00:10:59.440 --> 00:11:00.040
who said that.

00:11:00.040 --> 00:11:01.990
So I'm not really sure
where they found it.

00:11:01.990 --> 00:11:05.270
Anyway, and then the
next conversation

00:11:05.270 --> 00:11:07.180
was somebody else who
said, "we should just

00:11:07.180 --> 00:11:09.990
disband the entire
American police force.

00:11:09.990 --> 00:11:11.822
We don't need to
believe anymore."

00:11:11.822 --> 00:11:14.809
So very productive
rational conversation

00:11:14.809 --> 00:11:15.600
that was happening.

00:11:15.600 --> 00:11:17.641
And then in between, it
was just people literally

00:11:17.641 --> 00:11:19.159
screaming at the
top of their lungs,

00:11:19.159 --> 00:11:20.450
as loud as they possibly could.

00:11:20.450 --> 00:11:22.260
And in between, and
this is the part

00:11:22.260 --> 00:11:25.050
that I think that is
so heartbreaking to me,

00:11:25.050 --> 00:11:28.410
in between, Megyn Kelly, who
I really do respect and think

00:11:28.410 --> 00:11:30.900
is an incredibly smart
and gifted person,

00:11:30.900 --> 00:11:33.150
Megyn Kelly was thrilled.

00:11:33.150 --> 00:11:36.580
And at the commercial break,
she encouraged us to keep at it.

00:11:36.580 --> 00:11:39.528
Because it makes
for great ratings.

00:11:39.528 --> 00:11:41.610
So think about that.

00:11:41.610 --> 00:11:44.590
Is that really where we
want to be as a country?

00:11:44.590 --> 00:11:46.587
So in the context
of all of this,

00:11:46.587 --> 00:11:48.920
part of what I try to do in
"Crossing the Thinnest Line"

00:11:48.920 --> 00:11:53.450
is paint a picture of
not just what's at stake.

00:11:53.450 --> 00:11:55.240
And what's at stake is enormous.

00:11:55.240 --> 00:11:57.050
We have a lot at
stake economically.

00:11:57.050 --> 00:12:00.070
We certainly have a
lot at stake socially.

00:12:00.070 --> 00:12:02.820
It is critically important
to the future of our country

00:12:02.820 --> 00:12:06.150
that we do better in
terms of inclusion

00:12:06.150 --> 00:12:09.750
and this overall approach
that we take to the fact

00:12:09.750 --> 00:12:12.660
that our nation will, in
less than a generation,

00:12:12.660 --> 00:12:15.150
be a minority majority nation.

00:12:15.150 --> 00:12:17.490
We are seeing the
sort of anxiety

00:12:17.490 --> 00:12:19.630
and the backlash
again that really come

00:12:19.630 --> 00:12:21.110
to the fore in this election.

00:12:21.110 --> 00:12:22.484
I think that is
actually probably

00:12:22.484 --> 00:12:26.140
one of the most salient pieces
of what's happening today

00:12:26.140 --> 00:12:30.870
is this discomfort that many,
especially white Americans have

00:12:30.870 --> 00:12:32.450
with the changing
face of our nation.

00:12:32.450 --> 00:12:33.949
I don't think you
can deny that that

00:12:33.949 --> 00:12:35.900
is a significant
undercurrent here.

00:12:35.900 --> 00:12:38.035
But what it takes to
do better, I think,

00:12:38.035 --> 00:12:40.160
and we're going to talk
about one small piece of it

00:12:40.160 --> 00:12:43.580
today, the media and
Hollywood piece of it, which

00:12:43.580 --> 00:12:45.450
might seem like
the least important

00:12:45.450 --> 00:12:47.011
but actually has a role to play.

00:12:47.011 --> 00:12:49.260
In the book, I try to make
the case that it's actually

00:12:49.260 --> 00:12:50.260
a whole bunch of things.

00:12:50.260 --> 00:12:52.490
It's not just about
how much better

00:12:52.490 --> 00:12:55.059
do we do on diversity
at a company like Google

00:12:55.059 --> 00:12:57.350
or at any American company,
which is mostly where we're

00:12:57.350 --> 00:12:58.500
talking about diversity today.

00:12:58.500 --> 00:13:00.880
We are mostly talking about
it in the corporate context,

00:13:00.880 --> 00:13:01.380
right?

00:13:01.380 --> 00:13:03.088
How to get more women
and people of color

00:13:03.088 --> 00:13:05.506
to go into STEM, how our
businesses can do better,

00:13:05.506 --> 00:13:07.256
how to have more women
and people of color

00:13:07.256 --> 00:13:09.330
on corporate boards
and in the C-Suite.

00:13:09.330 --> 00:13:14.260
That matters, but there's
a whole panoply of factors.

00:13:14.260 --> 00:13:17.040
One of them is what's
happening in education

00:13:17.040 --> 00:13:19.314
and I talked about my
own formative experience.

00:13:19.314 --> 00:13:20.980
Unfortunately, the
trends in the country

00:13:20.980 --> 00:13:22.520
are not going in the right way.

00:13:22.520 --> 00:13:23.910
If you look at
the charts of what

00:13:23.910 --> 00:13:26.020
happened to school
integration since Brown

00:13:26.020 --> 00:13:28.920
vs. Board of education,
it is a bell curve,

00:13:28.920 --> 00:13:30.400
and the trend of reversing.

00:13:30.400 --> 00:13:33.910
So American public schools
are now becoming less diverse.

00:13:33.910 --> 00:13:35.970
And it is actually
the private schools,

00:13:35.970 --> 00:13:38.580
in many ways, so for the
folks who can afford it,

00:13:38.580 --> 00:13:40.540
who get to send their
kids to private schools.

00:13:40.540 --> 00:13:41.620
The private schools
are working overtime

00:13:41.620 --> 00:13:43.280
to try to make sure
they're diverse.

00:13:43.280 --> 00:13:45.030
But our public school
system is becoming

00:13:45.030 --> 00:13:46.420
more segregated than ever.

00:13:46.420 --> 00:13:48.480
And I talk a lot about
that in the book.

00:13:48.480 --> 00:13:50.920
So we're maybe preparing
the next generation

00:13:50.920 --> 00:13:52.830
to potentially reverse
some of the gains that

00:13:52.830 --> 00:13:54.190
have been made with
Gen Y and Gen Z

00:13:54.190 --> 00:13:55.530
and some of the
younger Americans.

00:13:55.530 --> 00:13:56.071
I don't know.

00:13:56.071 --> 00:13:57.500
It's a question.

00:13:57.500 --> 00:14:00.370
We have a challenge
around mass incarceration,

00:14:00.370 --> 00:14:02.740
which you absolutely cannot
separate from the larger

00:14:02.740 --> 00:14:05.210
question of how are we doing
on diversity in this country.

00:14:05.210 --> 00:14:08.250
We are locking up
an entire generation

00:14:08.250 --> 00:14:10.214
of minority Americans.

00:14:10.214 --> 00:14:11.714
And if we don't
address that and see

00:14:11.714 --> 00:14:14.300
that as part of the overall
picture of diversity

00:14:14.300 --> 00:14:17.660
in the country, we are missing
a very important and significant

00:14:17.660 --> 00:14:18.709
piece.

00:14:18.709 --> 00:14:20.500
Obviously, the business
piece is important.

00:14:20.500 --> 00:14:23.390
Immigration continues to be,
especially in this election

00:14:23.390 --> 00:14:27.460
cycle, a really intense
topic of dispute and debate.

00:14:27.460 --> 00:14:28.940
But of course--
and I know you all

00:14:28.940 --> 00:14:32.240
know this in a company
like Google-- immigrants

00:14:32.240 --> 00:14:35.010
to the country, including, by
the way, those who are here

00:14:35.010 --> 00:14:37.480
who are undocumented,
contribute enormously

00:14:37.480 --> 00:14:38.560
to the American economy.

00:14:38.560 --> 00:14:41.020
Undocumented
immigrants pay billions

00:14:41.020 --> 00:14:43.050
of dollars in taxes
every year, which

00:14:43.050 --> 00:14:45.050
is an extraordinary piece
of the picture which

00:14:45.050 --> 00:14:46.880
doesn't get much attention.

00:14:46.880 --> 00:14:49.180
And then what I want to
invite Alysia to talk about

00:14:49.180 --> 00:14:52.190
with me in a minute is this
entertainment and media piece,

00:14:52.190 --> 00:14:55.889
which seems silly in the
context of talking about some

00:14:55.889 --> 00:14:57.930
of the big issues we have
around criminal justice

00:14:57.930 --> 00:15:01.880
reform and education
and immigration, right?

00:15:01.880 --> 00:15:05.680
But part of what I argue in
the book is but what we see

00:15:05.680 --> 00:15:08.050
and what we see
intensely all the time

00:15:08.050 --> 00:15:13.030
now because of the boundaryless
sources of information

00:15:13.030 --> 00:15:17.110
that come at us, what we see
in the media, in Hollywood,

00:15:17.110 --> 00:15:20.290
on television, maybe
matters more than ever.

00:15:20.290 --> 00:15:21.970
And the challenge
is that we have not

00:15:21.970 --> 00:15:24.950
made the kind of
progress in ensuring

00:15:24.950 --> 00:15:27.410
that the images and the
stories that we see actually

00:15:27.410 --> 00:15:29.120
represent our country.

00:15:29.120 --> 00:15:32.215
So I'm going to invite up Alysia
Reiner, my dear friend, who

00:15:32.215 --> 00:15:34.270
I'll also introduce to
come up and join me.

00:15:34.270 --> 00:15:35.728
We'll have a bit
of a conversation.

00:15:35.728 --> 00:15:38.295
We really want to encourage
you to participate in this.

00:15:38.295 --> 00:15:39.600
This is not just about me.

00:15:39.600 --> 00:15:42.510
And fundamentally for us to
make progress as a country,

00:15:42.510 --> 00:15:45.350
it takes a lot of conversation.

00:15:45.350 --> 00:15:46.725
And then the last
thing I'll just

00:15:46.725 --> 00:15:48.810
say about this is
that I do think--

00:15:48.810 --> 00:15:51.724
and I write a lot about
this in the book-- I do

00:15:51.724 --> 00:15:56.200
believe that white America has
an outsized responsibility.

00:15:56.200 --> 00:15:59.580
And white male America
in many instances

00:15:59.580 --> 00:16:02.660
has an outsized responsibility
in solving these issues

00:16:02.660 --> 00:16:04.940
and in finding a
way to understand.

00:16:04.940 --> 00:16:07.860
The one point I managed to make
on Megyn Kelly's crazy show

00:16:07.860 --> 00:16:12.880
that day is that, in the end,
it doesn't matter whether or not

00:16:12.880 --> 00:16:16.200
I can understand in a
personal or a deep way

00:16:16.200 --> 00:16:19.692
the experience of what
it's like to drive around

00:16:19.692 --> 00:16:21.150
the country as an
African-American.

00:16:21.150 --> 00:16:22.910
I will never understand that.

00:16:22.910 --> 00:16:24.130
I'm a white person.

00:16:24.130 --> 00:16:27.070
I can never fully appreciate
what that feels like.

00:16:27.070 --> 00:16:29.600
But I have a responsibility,
and I believe we all

00:16:29.600 --> 00:16:34.560
do, that if any American, if any
American feels that they do not

00:16:34.560 --> 00:16:36.960
have full access to
the American dream,

00:16:36.960 --> 00:16:41.940
or that they are in any way
have less than the full rights

00:16:41.940 --> 00:16:45.100
and privileges and equality
of all other American,

00:16:45.100 --> 00:16:47.160
then we all have
a responsibility

00:16:47.160 --> 00:16:50.100
to try to make it better,
whether we agree with it

00:16:50.100 --> 00:16:51.604
or relate to it or not.

00:16:51.604 --> 00:16:53.020
And so all the
conversations we're

00:16:53.020 --> 00:16:54.580
having today about "I
believe it's racist,"

00:16:54.580 --> 00:16:56.990
"I don't believe it's racist,"
"I think the cops are racist,"

00:16:56.990 --> 00:16:59.365
"I don't think the cops are
racist,"-- it doesn't matter.

00:16:59.365 --> 00:17:00.590
None of it matters.

00:17:00.590 --> 00:17:04.790
Because if any Americans
feel-- if any American feel

00:17:04.790 --> 00:17:07.329
that our country is
not a full meritocracy,

00:17:07.329 --> 00:17:10.319
is not fully accessible, that
the American dream is not

00:17:10.319 --> 00:17:14.349
accessible to all Americans,
then we all have work to do.

00:17:14.349 --> 00:17:16.510
So with that, I want to
invite up Alysia Reiner,

00:17:16.510 --> 00:17:17.630
the amazing and talented.

00:17:17.630 --> 00:17:20.084
I know many of you know her.

00:17:20.084 --> 00:17:22.910
I'm very lucky that Alysia and
I have been very dear friends

00:17:22.910 --> 00:17:24.150
for a long time.

00:17:24.150 --> 00:17:25.401
We're actually neighbors.

00:17:25.401 --> 00:17:27.900
We both live in Harlem and have
lived there for a long time.

00:17:27.900 --> 00:17:30.470
Our little girls
are the same age.

00:17:30.470 --> 00:17:33.070
And Alysia doesn't meed
a ton of introduction.

00:17:33.070 --> 00:17:35.510
I'm sure you have seen her
on the amazing show "Orange

00:17:35.510 --> 00:17:38.050
is the New Black,"
which is one of the few

00:17:38.050 --> 00:17:39.830
shows out there--
it's certainly one

00:17:39.830 --> 00:17:42.170
of the only shows with an
all female cast or a majority

00:17:42.170 --> 00:17:45.130
female cast, one
of the few shows

00:17:45.130 --> 00:17:49.240
that also has really focused
on the mass incarceration issue

00:17:49.240 --> 00:17:52.050
as one of the
themes of the show.

00:17:52.050 --> 00:17:54.580
Alysia, along with many of the
cast members and the writers

00:17:54.580 --> 00:17:57.660
have also put a lot of
time into calling attention

00:17:57.660 --> 00:18:00.800
to criminal justice reform and
mass incarceration of women,

00:18:00.800 --> 00:18:01.760
which is important.

00:18:01.760 --> 00:18:04.490
And her new movie,
"Equity," which

00:18:04.490 --> 00:18:06.050
she was here at Google when?

00:18:06.050 --> 00:18:07.480
Like a month ago?

00:18:07.480 --> 00:18:09.090
Yeah, a month ago to talk about.

00:18:09.090 --> 00:18:14.410
It's the first all-female driven
movie, a Wall Street film,

00:18:14.410 --> 00:18:18.060
that was written by,
directed by, and starred in

00:18:18.060 --> 00:18:20.680
by-- that's not really
a sentence-- all women.

00:18:20.680 --> 00:18:23.010
And I've been talking
with her about that movie

00:18:23.010 --> 00:18:24.730
for a very long time.

00:18:24.730 --> 00:18:27.395
So please join me in
welcoming Alysia Reiner.

00:18:27.395 --> 00:18:29.620
[APPLAUSE]

