LAUREN LEADER
CHIVEE: How are you?

00:18:33.230 --> 00:18:34.589
ALYSIA REINER: I'm good.

00:18:34.589 --> 00:18:35.245
Am I on.

00:18:35.245 --> 00:18:36.870
LAUREN LEADER CHIVEE:
I think she's on.

00:18:36.870 --> 00:18:37.490
Is she on?

00:18:37.490 --> 00:18:39.790
She's not on.

00:18:39.790 --> 00:18:40.690
Are we on the screen?

00:18:40.690 --> 00:18:43.570
Can they see us in California?

00:18:43.570 --> 00:18:46.830
California, Houston,
are you there?

00:18:46.830 --> 00:18:51.200
So I started to say
that in many ways

00:18:51.200 --> 00:18:55.350
it's hard to think of
Hollywood, or movies, or TV,

00:18:55.350 --> 00:18:58.642
which is fun and fluffy, right?

00:18:58.642 --> 00:19:01.740
Sexy and fun and fluffy,
it's hard to think about that

00:19:01.740 --> 00:19:06.450
as having an important role
to play in the context of all

00:19:06.450 --> 00:19:08.000
the rest of this.

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:09.970
But I know that I
often talk about it

00:19:09.970 --> 00:19:12.860
and I say-- I tell this story in
the book that when I was a kid,

00:19:12.860 --> 00:19:16.720
one of the most influential
women that I saw on television

00:19:16.720 --> 00:19:18.270
was Wonder Woman.

00:19:18.270 --> 00:19:21.410
And Wonder Woman
was at her height

00:19:21.410 --> 00:19:24.580
of power in my early childhood.

00:19:24.580 --> 00:19:26.180
Lynda Carter lived
in Washington.

00:19:26.180 --> 00:19:27.450
And that was also a
big thing, and she

00:19:27.450 --> 00:19:28.975
lived in my
neighborhood and I used

00:19:28.975 --> 00:19:30.340
to ride my bike past
her house, always

00:19:30.340 --> 00:19:31.705
trying to get a glimpse
of her because I

00:19:31.705 --> 00:19:32.746
was so obsessed with her.

00:19:32.746 --> 00:19:33.540
I never saw her.

00:19:33.540 --> 00:19:35.880
But Wonder Woman kicked ass.

00:19:35.880 --> 00:19:39.140
I mean, she was an
absolute feminist icon.

00:19:39.140 --> 00:19:41.730
And for me, it made
a big difference.

00:19:41.730 --> 00:19:43.797
But it does feel
like in some ways--

00:19:43.797 --> 00:19:45.380
and I think the
numbers bear this out,

00:19:45.380 --> 00:19:50.320
and I know you know them really
well-- this sort of early '80s,

00:19:50.320 --> 00:19:54.220
late '70s, early '80s, in
many ways was a high point.

00:19:54.220 --> 00:19:57.500
We haven't really seen
a substantial increase

00:19:57.500 --> 00:20:04.410
in women role models in the
movies and on TV since then.

00:20:04.410 --> 00:20:07.270
ALYSIA REINER: I am here
later today for the Gina Davis

00:20:07.270 --> 00:20:09.670
Symposium, in which
we'll talk about

00:20:09.670 --> 00:20:13.770
not only the actual
statistics but perhaps

00:20:13.770 --> 00:20:16.910
a piece of technology that
Google is involved with

00:20:16.910 --> 00:20:18.770
to look at these statistics.

00:20:18.770 --> 00:20:21.770
And I just want to roll
it back for a second

00:20:21.770 --> 00:20:25.350
and say thank you for
everything that you've said.

00:20:25.350 --> 00:20:30.130
Also as a very
privileged white woman,

00:20:30.130 --> 00:20:34.920
I grew up thinking I
was outrageously lucky.

00:20:34.920 --> 00:20:37.750
And I was teased mercilessly.

00:20:37.750 --> 00:20:39.390
We now call it bullying.

00:20:39.390 --> 00:20:43.400
But I was the fat kid
and teased mercilessly.

00:20:43.400 --> 00:20:47.080
And there were this
interesting dichotomy of "oh,

00:20:47.080 --> 00:20:48.520
I feel like the outsider.

00:20:48.520 --> 00:20:49.910
I feel like crap."

00:20:49.910 --> 00:20:56.450
But I went to a very privileged
white fairly diverse school,

00:20:56.450 --> 00:21:00.370
but was made aware
because it was a very--

00:21:00.370 --> 00:21:02.090
it was ethical
culture which makes

00:21:02.090 --> 00:21:06.250
you very aware of your
privilege and aware of the world

00:21:06.250 --> 00:21:06.880
around you.

00:21:06.880 --> 00:21:11.840
And we learned ethics
in first grade.

00:21:11.840 --> 00:21:16.730
And I felt very "like how dare
I feel anything but lucky."

00:21:16.730 --> 00:21:24.420
That's pretty much
how I grew up and felt

00:21:24.420 --> 00:21:28.860
a similar responsibility to
make change for others, not

00:21:28.860 --> 00:21:30.010
for myself.

00:21:30.010 --> 00:21:33.690
So I think coming to a
place where I was really

00:21:33.690 --> 00:21:37.680
looking at the statistics
about women in the media

00:21:37.680 --> 00:21:43.170
took me a long time, because
I had this "how dare I"

00:21:43.170 --> 00:21:44.380
mentality.

00:21:44.380 --> 00:21:48.150
And then I did become
aware of the statistics.

00:21:48.150 --> 00:21:51.710
And a lot of it had to do
with becoming a mother for me.

00:21:51.710 --> 00:21:57.340
Because what you said about
"if you see it, you can be it,"

00:21:57.340 --> 00:22:00.620
I became the mother of
a girl, of a daughter,

00:22:00.620 --> 00:22:04.260
and I wanted her to
see certain things.

00:22:04.260 --> 00:22:09.106
And I then did some research.

00:22:09.106 --> 00:22:11.400
And Stacey Smith does
some amazing research.

00:22:11.400 --> 00:22:13.640
The Gina Davis Institute
does some amazing research.

00:22:13.640 --> 00:22:17.260
And what I found out is
77% of the people you

00:22:17.260 --> 00:22:21.480
see in all of media, which
includes film, television,

00:22:21.480 --> 00:22:26.680
cartoons-- everything,
75% are male.

00:22:26.680 --> 00:22:30.540
So when you're looking
at that as a human being,

00:22:30.540 --> 00:22:35.272
as a female human being, you
feel like a massive minority.

00:22:35.272 --> 00:22:36.720
As I explained it to my--

00:22:36.720 --> 00:22:38.470
LAUREN LEADER CHIVEE:
Which is ridiculous.

00:22:38.470 --> 00:22:39.803
ALYSIA REINER: Because it's not.

00:22:39.803 --> 00:22:44.370
And as a male, you feel
like you own the world.

00:22:44.370 --> 00:22:47.675
And that is something that
we're seeing every day.

