00:23:03.587 --> 00:23:05.170
But one of the most
interesting things

00:23:05.170 --> 00:23:07.220
that I heard somebody say
after seeing "Equity,"

00:23:07.220 --> 00:23:10.550
was a friend of mine
went with her husband--

00:23:10.550 --> 00:23:12.070
and if you've not
seen the movie,

00:23:12.070 --> 00:23:14.500
the female characters
really drive the movie.

00:23:14.500 --> 00:23:16.740
And it is the story of
women, a very important story

00:23:16.740 --> 00:23:17.740
of women on Wall Street.

00:23:17.740 --> 00:23:19.200
It's also a thriller.

00:23:19.200 --> 00:23:22.100
It's not overtly about
women in a traditional way,

00:23:22.100 --> 00:23:23.920
but it is driven by women.

00:23:23.920 --> 00:23:26.275
And one of the things that
my friend's husband said

00:23:26.275 --> 00:23:28.650
to her was "the male
characters are so one

00:23:28.650 --> 00:23:30.712
dimensional and thinly drawn."

00:23:30.712 --> 00:23:31.460
And she's like--

00:23:31.460 --> 00:23:32.660
ALYSIA REINER:
Welcome to our world.

00:23:32.660 --> 00:23:33.970
LAUREN LEADER CHIVEE:
Yeah, welcome to our world.

00:23:33.970 --> 00:23:35.970
Because if you look at
movies like "Wall Street"

00:23:35.970 --> 00:23:37.636
or any of these movies,
I mean, I think,

00:23:37.636 --> 00:23:39.890
when I watched it the first
time, I started laughing.

00:23:39.890 --> 00:23:41.052
Because of course
the first time you

00:23:41.052 --> 00:23:42.718
see a woman in "The
Wolf of Wall Street"

00:23:42.718 --> 00:23:45.634
is Margot Robbie naked
in the bubble bath.

00:23:45.634 --> 00:23:47.050
And you're like,
"seriously, guys?

00:23:47.050 --> 00:23:48.050
Really?"

00:23:48.050 --> 00:23:54.040
And then the next one is the
sniveling, insecure secretary.

00:23:54.040 --> 00:23:55.850
Anyway, you get the point.

00:23:55.850 --> 00:23:58.270
But the point is that one
of the things that I thought

00:23:58.270 --> 00:24:00.900
was so interesting is
this week with the Emmys

00:24:00.900 --> 00:24:04.090
and of course after the Oscars
so White controversy last year,

00:24:04.090 --> 00:24:06.630
which is, by the way, not over.

00:24:06.630 --> 00:24:08.322
So stay tuned for February.

00:24:08.322 --> 00:24:10.405
We'll see if there's any
significant improvements.

00:24:10.405 --> 00:24:12.127
It's unlikely.

00:24:12.127 --> 00:24:13.710
But one thing that's
super interesting

00:24:13.710 --> 00:24:16.640
is that the Emmys this
year were so focused.

00:24:16.640 --> 00:24:18.402
There was much
attention on diversity,

00:24:18.402 --> 00:24:19.860
shows like
"Transparent" and others

00:24:19.860 --> 00:24:21.400
that got a lot of attention.

00:24:21.400 --> 00:24:24.780
So you might conclude
that TV is doing

00:24:24.780 --> 00:24:28.491
pretty well, that there's
Shondaland and all the things,

00:24:28.491 --> 00:24:28.990
right?

00:24:31.534 --> 00:24:36.370
ALYSIA REINER: It's
disturbing when

00:24:36.370 --> 00:24:38.845
there is information like that.

00:24:38.845 --> 00:24:42.770
Yeah, that makes us feel
like "oh, we're doing great,"

00:24:42.770 --> 00:24:45.550
because statistically
speaking, we're not.

00:24:45.550 --> 00:24:49.750
And statistically
speaking, 8% of directors

00:24:49.750 --> 00:24:54.700
are women, similar
to 8% of female CEOs.

00:24:54.700 --> 00:25:01.090
And we do have, I think,
1% or 2% cinematographers.

00:25:01.090 --> 00:25:06.680
We do have that 77%
gap, even in the extras

00:25:06.680 --> 00:25:12.320
you see in the background,
in bizonker crowd scenes.

00:25:12.320 --> 00:25:14.185
So how do we change that?

00:25:16.980 --> 00:25:18.929
And "Equity" was a
big piece of that.

00:25:18.929 --> 00:25:20.720
LAUREN LEADER CHIVEE:
So I think part of it

00:25:20.720 --> 00:25:23.690
is too-- you talked
about your daughter

00:25:23.690 --> 00:25:25.440
and I haven't talked
about my kids,

00:25:25.440 --> 00:25:28.390
but it is an important
piece of the puzzle which

00:25:28.390 --> 00:25:31.110
I didn't mention, which is
that both my daughters are

00:25:31.110 --> 00:25:32.510
African-American.

00:25:32.510 --> 00:25:40.110
And so when I think about what
I want for them, obviously,

00:25:40.110 --> 00:25:42.900
at her age, I'm glad we have
"Doc McStuffins," which,

00:25:42.900 --> 00:25:46.220
by the way, just got
cancelled, if you didn't know.

00:25:46.220 --> 00:25:49.489
Tragic loss in Disneyland, "Doc
McStuffins" has been cancelled.

00:25:49.489 --> 00:25:50.530
My daughter's devastated.

00:25:50.530 --> 00:25:53.350
She's seen every episode
at least 100 times.

00:25:53.350 --> 00:25:57.952
But that question of what
an impact it really makes.

00:25:57.952 --> 00:25:59.410
And I talk a little
bit in the book

00:25:59.410 --> 00:26:01.610
about the impact
of "The Cosby Show"

00:26:01.610 --> 00:26:04.950
and how groundbreaking that
was for so many Americans.

00:26:04.950 --> 00:26:06.900
And I think now in some
ways "Master of None"

00:26:06.900 --> 00:26:09.340
is breaking that territory
for Asian-Americans.

00:26:09.340 --> 00:26:12.000
We've seen so few
Asian-Americans ever

00:26:12.000 --> 00:26:13.770
in his speech at
the Emmys, right?

00:26:13.770 --> 00:26:15.290
ALYSIA REINER:
"Fresh off the Boat."

00:26:15.290 --> 00:26:15.580
LAUREN LEADER CHIVEE:
"Fresh off of the Boat."

00:26:15.580 --> 00:26:17.160
I mean, this is
the biggest deal.

00:26:17.160 --> 00:26:21.110
I mean, these are huge
segments of American society,

00:26:21.110 --> 00:26:23.130
and yet we barely see them.

00:26:23.130 --> 00:26:26.750
So Alysia, what's the problem?

00:26:26.750 --> 00:26:29.270
Given that there's a good
economic case, certainly

00:26:29.270 --> 00:26:32.362
in Hollywood, the movies and
the shows that do actually

00:26:32.362 --> 00:26:33.820
reflect the country
do really well.

00:26:33.820 --> 00:26:37.640
I mean, you look at how "Frozen"
became the highest grossing

00:26:37.640 --> 00:26:39.356
animated film of all time.

00:26:39.356 --> 00:26:42.515
So why is it so
hard to make change

00:26:42.515 --> 00:26:48.329
and to see stories in Hollywood
that look like America?

00:26:48.329 --> 00:26:49.870
ALYSIA REINER: In
my experience, it's

00:26:49.870 --> 00:26:51.590
a couple of different things.

00:26:51.590 --> 00:26:54.020
One is our unconscious bias.

00:26:54.020 --> 00:26:57.890
I think there are
so many parts of us

00:26:57.890 --> 00:27:00.650
that we are simply not aware of.

00:27:00.650 --> 00:27:06.670
And you were talking earlier
about the overresponsibility

00:27:06.670 --> 00:27:09.820
of the white male, and I
really believe that to be true.

00:27:09.820 --> 00:27:10.320
Because--

00:27:10.320 --> 00:27:12.320
LAUREN LEADER CHIVEE:
Because they're in power.

00:27:12.320 --> 00:27:16.910
ALYSIA REINER: A, they
are in power, and B,

00:27:16.910 --> 00:27:21.780
I feel like there are so
many systems in place that

00:27:21.780 --> 00:27:23.190
are habit.

00:27:23.190 --> 00:27:24.765
We all have our habits.

00:27:24.765 --> 00:27:25.890
LAUREN LEADER CHIVEE: Yeah.

00:27:25.890 --> 00:27:28.570
ALYSIA REINER: And some of
them are good and some of them

00:27:28.570 --> 00:27:29.500
are bad.

00:27:29.500 --> 00:27:35.320
Hiring our friends is a big
habit a lot of people have.

00:27:35.320 --> 00:27:38.160
Hiring people that
look like you,

00:27:38.160 --> 00:27:42.360
that feel like you, that
you're comfortable with,

00:27:42.360 --> 00:27:45.859
is just a truth that
most of the world does.

00:27:45.859 --> 00:27:47.650
LAUREN LEADER CHIVEE:
I mean, I always make

00:27:47.650 --> 00:27:50.420
the joke that like Karen's
my key demographic, right?

00:27:50.420 --> 00:27:53.575
Nice Jewish girls from a
similar background to me.

00:27:53.575 --> 00:27:56.890
I totally was biased
in my hiring of Karen.

00:27:56.890 --> 00:27:59.740
ALYSIA REINER: And I'm going
to talk about it for myself.

00:27:59.740 --> 00:28:01.198
LAUREN LEADER
CHIVEE: We all do it.

00:28:01.198 --> 00:28:02.266
We all do it.

00:28:02.266 --> 00:28:04.510
ALYSIA REINER: I was at
a screening of "Equity."

00:28:04.510 --> 00:28:09.670
I did a Q&amp;A. And this
girl who looked just

00:28:09.670 --> 00:28:12.670
like one of the
girls I grew up with,

00:28:12.670 --> 00:28:15.550
looked like in Upper West
Side girl, came up to me

00:28:15.550 --> 00:28:17.130
and started talking to me.

00:28:17.130 --> 00:28:19.420
And her daughter
goes to Bank Street.

00:28:19.420 --> 00:28:21.200
My daughter goes to Bank Street.

00:28:21.200 --> 00:28:23.720
And all of a sudden,
we're friends.

00:28:23.720 --> 00:28:28.770
And I don't know if that would
have happened if it was a man.

00:28:28.770 --> 00:28:32.120
Probably not, first of
all because I'm married.

00:28:32.120 --> 00:28:38.180
And I only say that
because if I was a man

00:28:38.180 --> 00:28:41.970
and a woman came up to
me, that's not cool.

00:28:41.970 --> 00:28:44.302
So I'm not going
to hire that woman,

00:28:44.302 --> 00:28:46.510
or I'm not going to maybe
be friends with that women,

00:28:46.510 --> 00:28:48.520
because what is my
wife going to think?

00:28:48.520 --> 00:28:53.480
And these are these
unconscious biases,

00:28:53.480 --> 00:28:58.480
these stereotypes that we
aren't aware of sometimes,

00:28:58.480 --> 00:29:00.147
that we have to make
ourselves aware of.

00:29:00.147 --> 00:29:02.480
LAUREN LEADER CHIVEE: I mean,
I'm controversial on this,

00:29:02.480 --> 00:29:05.110
though, because I will say
that I don't actually subscribe

00:29:05.110 --> 00:29:06.630
to it always being unconscious.

00:29:06.630 --> 00:29:08.620
And it actually makes
me a little crazy,

00:29:08.620 --> 00:29:11.010
because I often feel like
the constant conversation

00:29:11.010 --> 00:29:14.230
about unconscious bias sometimes
lets people off the hook.

00:29:14.230 --> 00:29:16.650
Like, "oh, I just
wasn't conscious.

00:29:16.650 --> 00:29:17.630
No, no.

00:29:17.630 --> 00:29:18.970
It doesn't work that way.

00:29:18.970 --> 00:29:21.710
You don't get to be unconscious.

00:29:21.710 --> 00:29:24.984
By the way, I think sometimes
it is absolutely blatantly

00:29:24.984 --> 00:29:25.920
conscious.

00:29:25.920 --> 00:29:30.230
Some of the biases that we are
seeing in this election cycle,

00:29:30.230 --> 00:29:33.200
you can't tell me that people
aren't conscious of the fact

00:29:33.200 --> 00:29:36.220
that we don't ask men
to smile when they're

00:29:36.220 --> 00:29:39.300
running for president, and yet
we ask women to smile, right?

00:29:39.300 --> 00:29:42.520
So I get really
fired up about this.

00:29:42.520 --> 00:29:45.599
One thing i just wanted to
share is that part of why I--

00:29:45.599 --> 00:29:47.640
and this is not to be a
pain-in-the-ass about it,

00:29:47.640 --> 00:29:50.540
but I do think it's
not an excuse anymore.

00:29:50.540 --> 00:29:52.910
Unconscious bias doesn't
get to be an excuse forever.

00:29:52.910 --> 00:29:55.470
"Oh, I wasn't conscious,
and so I just-- oops.

00:29:55.470 --> 00:29:56.560
My bad."

00:29:56.560 --> 00:29:58.870
We have to got beyond
that as a country.

00:29:58.870 --> 00:30:00.500
We have to do better than that.

00:30:00.500 --> 00:30:03.474
And one of the reasons why
I called the book "Crossing

00:30:03.474 --> 00:30:04.890
the Thinnest Line,"
and I did want

00:30:04.890 --> 00:30:06.079
to briefly tell this story.

00:30:06.079 --> 00:30:08.120
Alysia knows the story,
but I'll tell it briefly.

00:30:08.120 --> 00:30:11.100
It's that I have these
two fabulous colleagues,

00:30:11.100 --> 00:30:14.700
these lovely guys who
work with me in Boston.

00:30:14.700 --> 00:30:18.084
And they are these central
casting, white, Bostonian,

00:30:18.084 --> 00:30:20.360
Catholic guys.

00:30:20.360 --> 00:30:23.000
And you would not
look at them and think

00:30:23.000 --> 00:30:26.690
that they were-- I made
a lot of assumptions

00:30:26.690 --> 00:30:29.970
about them, as we always do
about everyone that we meet.

00:30:29.970 --> 00:30:33.540
Well, it turns out that my
colleague, Brian and Shawn,

00:30:33.540 --> 00:30:37.610
are part of the incredible
prison ministry in Boston.

00:30:37.610 --> 00:30:40.880
And they, along with a
bunch of other mostly white

00:30:40.880 --> 00:30:44.000
male executives from a
bunch of awesome companies,

00:30:44.000 --> 00:30:47.910
are part of a parish that
goes into largely minority--

00:30:47.910 --> 00:30:51.150
because that is who the
prison population is--

00:30:51.150 --> 00:30:54.110
maximum security prisons
around the Boston area

00:30:54.110 --> 00:30:57.550
and do these amazing of
collaborative ministries.

00:30:57.550 --> 00:30:59.500
And the thing that Bryan
said to me about it

00:30:59.500 --> 00:31:02.430
is why I titled the
book the way I did.

00:31:02.430 --> 00:31:04.640
And he blew me away
when he said this.

00:31:04.640 --> 00:31:06.260
He said after visiting
these prisons--

00:31:06.260 --> 00:31:07.240
and he was terrified to do it.

00:31:07.240 --> 00:31:09.698
He thought "what am I going to
have to say to these people?

00:31:09.698 --> 00:31:11.515
What do I have in
common with them?"

00:31:11.515 --> 00:31:13.652
After the first
visit, he walked out

00:31:13.652 --> 00:31:17.750
and said, "The line
between us is so very thin.

00:31:17.750 --> 00:31:20.580
If I had made one different
decision in my life,

00:31:20.580 --> 00:31:21.875
I might be where they are.

00:31:21.875 --> 00:31:23.700
If they had made one
different decision

00:31:23.700 --> 00:31:26.320
or had one different
opportunity in their lives,

00:31:26.320 --> 00:31:28.160
they might be where I am."

00:31:28.160 --> 00:31:32.600
And I was so blown away that
he thought of that as a thin,

00:31:32.600 --> 00:31:34.530
that he actually
saw there being so

00:31:34.530 --> 00:31:36.880
little difference between them.

00:31:36.880 --> 00:31:39.282
And I thought,
"that's what we need.

00:31:39.282 --> 00:31:40.740
That's what we need
in the country,

00:31:40.740 --> 00:31:44.434
is we need more people to
see these lines as thin."

00:31:44.434 --> 00:31:46.610
And so I want to open
it up, because I think

00:31:46.610 --> 00:31:47.860
we should have a conversation.

00:31:47.860 --> 00:31:52.640
But Hollywood does have
this amazing ability

00:31:52.640 --> 00:31:54.880
through storytelling
to help people

00:31:54.880 --> 00:31:59.010
relate to other human beings
they might not otherwise

00:31:59.010 --> 00:31:59.960
relate to.

00:31:59.960 --> 00:32:02.630
So what are you seeing?

00:32:02.630 --> 00:32:03.960
What are your signs of hope?

00:32:03.960 --> 00:32:06.000
What do you see changing people?

00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:09.350
What do you think is the
possibility for that?

00:32:09.350 --> 00:32:11.030
Are we moving?

00:32:11.030 --> 00:32:14.692
The pace is glacial, but are
you optimistic, pessimistic?

00:32:14.692 --> 00:32:16.150
ALYSIA REINER: I'm
very optimistic.

00:32:16.150 --> 00:32:19.540
I think I am by
nature an optimist.

00:32:19.540 --> 00:32:25.080
And when you were talking about
how we make unconscious bias

00:32:25.080 --> 00:32:29.480
and that lets
people off the hook,

00:32:29.480 --> 00:32:31.025
I believe that we're good.

00:32:33.720 --> 00:32:36.470
I was at an event
yesterday, and they

00:32:36.470 --> 00:32:41.880
were talking about Einstein.

00:32:41.880 --> 00:32:45.550
He had this core
question-- do you believe

00:32:45.550 --> 00:32:49.060
the world is good or not?

00:32:49.060 --> 00:32:51.850
Do you believe that
we're all trying

00:32:51.850 --> 00:32:53.640
to make it better or not?

00:32:53.640 --> 00:32:58.600
And that really is a core
question, because if you do

00:32:58.600 --> 00:33:03.080
believe in the good, then
you act from the good.

00:33:03.080 --> 00:33:08.332
And I really believe in good.

00:33:08.332 --> 00:33:13.210
So I believe that we can only
teach with love and compassion

00:33:13.210 --> 00:33:15.670
and empathy and compassion.

00:33:15.670 --> 00:33:20.580
And so, yes, I believe we
are changing for the good.

00:33:20.580 --> 00:33:22.330
I really do.

00:33:22.330 --> 00:33:26.470
I think it takes a
lot of conversations

00:33:26.470 --> 00:33:31.120
like this and a lot of
talking about the things that

00:33:31.120 --> 00:33:33.900
are really painful
and uncomfortable

00:33:33.900 --> 00:33:35.450
and making art about it.

00:33:35.450 --> 00:33:40.140
And I became an
artist because I felt

00:33:40.140 --> 00:33:46.270
like that was the leave
where I could reach the most

00:33:46.270 --> 00:33:51.990
people with truths that they're
sometimes afraid to talk about

00:33:51.990 --> 00:33:52.615
in other areas.

00:33:52.615 --> 00:33:54.073
LAUREN LEADER
CHIVEE: Have you seen

00:33:54.073 --> 00:33:56.580
people changed through shows
like "Orange is the New Black?"

00:33:56.580 --> 00:33:58.538
I know you've had lots
of people come up to you

00:33:58.538 --> 00:33:59.920
and say things to you about it.

00:33:59.920 --> 00:34:00.530
ALYSIA REINER: Absolutely.

00:34:00.530 --> 00:34:01.880
LAUREN LEADER CHIVEE: So
would anyone stand out?

00:34:01.880 --> 00:34:03.421
What do you think
has been the change

00:34:03.421 --> 00:34:05.780
that a show like
"Orange" had made?

00:34:05.780 --> 00:34:08.761
ALYSIA REINER: I think it's
simply that thinnest line.

00:34:08.761 --> 00:34:10.969
LAUREN LEADER CHIVEE: People
relating to those women.

00:34:10.969 --> 00:34:13.900
ALYSIA REINER: And feeling
like that could be me.

00:34:13.900 --> 00:34:14.260
LAUREN LEADER
CHIVEE: Well, that's

00:34:14.260 --> 00:34:15.676
what the show does
so well, right?

00:34:15.676 --> 00:34:19.800
It's the stories of that
Piper's story too, right?

00:34:19.800 --> 00:34:21.370
ALYSIA REINER: And it's true.

00:34:21.370 --> 00:34:26.719
And how do we tell stories
that create more compassion?

00:34:26.719 --> 00:34:30.710
The first movie that
I made as a producer

00:34:30.710 --> 00:34:34.280
was a short about
grief and loss.

00:34:34.280 --> 00:34:36.659
I had lost my dad really
suddenly to cancer.

00:34:36.659 --> 00:34:38.360
He was 55.

00:34:38.360 --> 00:34:40.960
And I felt like a pariah.

00:34:40.960 --> 00:34:43.370
Everyone was afraid to talk
to me because they were

00:34:43.370 --> 00:34:45.260
so afraid to talk about death.

00:34:45.260 --> 00:34:47.009
And they didn't know
how to talk about it,

00:34:47.009 --> 00:34:48.889
so they just wouldn't.

00:34:48.889 --> 00:34:53.110
And so I made this movie, and I
worked with 10 grief counselors

00:34:53.110 --> 00:34:56.929
and social workers, and we
created basically some art

00:34:56.929 --> 00:35:00.320
therapy with all the
different phases of grieving.

00:35:00.320 --> 00:35:03.490
And we created a
discussion guide

00:35:03.490 --> 00:35:05.520
and a journal that
went with it as a way

00:35:05.520 --> 00:35:07.020
to help people process.

00:35:07.020 --> 00:35:10.570
And I do believe deeply in
this healing power of art

00:35:10.570 --> 00:35:14.190
or I wouldn't be here.

00:35:14.190 --> 00:35:18.840
I think it's hard
in moments like this

00:35:18.840 --> 00:35:20.720
and in what's going
on in the world,

00:35:20.720 --> 00:35:24.330
because you almost can't
make the art fast enough

00:35:24.330 --> 00:35:26.390
to really make impact.

00:35:26.390 --> 00:35:31.500
So then I think for me,
in a moment like this,

00:35:31.500 --> 00:35:34.610
especially as a white,
privileged woman,

00:35:34.610 --> 00:35:37.670
how do I make things happen?

00:35:37.670 --> 00:35:39.740
That's the biggest
question I turn over

00:35:39.740 --> 00:35:43.312
to you in these moments.

00:35:43.312 --> 00:35:45.770
LAUREN LEADER CHIVEE: I want
to open it up to conversation.

00:35:45.770 --> 00:35:47.880
I mentioned my kids,
one of the things

00:35:47.880 --> 00:35:50.412
that I learned, having worked
on diversity for years,

00:35:50.412 --> 00:35:52.620
one of the things I learned
when researching the book

00:35:52.620 --> 00:35:56.460
is how often minority Americans
talk to their children

00:35:56.460 --> 00:35:59.026
about race and how rarely
white Americans do.

00:36:01.961 --> 00:36:04.210
So I had a personal experience
of this, which I really

00:36:04.210 --> 00:36:06.500
had to face, which is that
when my daughter, Stella,

00:36:06.500 --> 00:36:09.310
who's now seven, came home from
preschool when she was three,

00:36:09.310 --> 00:36:11.594
she came home one day and
said, "Mama, I'm brown,"

00:36:11.594 --> 00:36:13.760
and wanted to talk about
the fact that she was brown

00:36:13.760 --> 00:36:15.385
and some of the other
kids in her class

00:36:15.385 --> 00:36:17.919
weren't, and it wasn't probably
as diverse as a preschool

00:36:17.919 --> 00:36:19.460
as I would have
liked for her, but it

00:36:19.460 --> 00:36:21.300
was the one that we picked.

00:36:21.300 --> 00:36:23.130
And if she wanted
to talk about it.

00:36:23.130 --> 00:36:26.570
And my immediate, visceral-- so
here was my unconscious thing,

00:36:26.570 --> 00:36:28.450
thinking I'm so
progressive about it--

00:36:28.450 --> 00:36:30.670
my immediate,
visceral reaction was

00:36:30.670 --> 00:36:33.200
I wanted to change the subject.

00:36:33.200 --> 00:36:35.736
And I thought, well, why am I
trying to change the subject?

00:36:35.736 --> 00:36:37.000
It's just an objective truth.

00:36:37.000 --> 00:36:37.540
What am I going to do?

00:36:37.540 --> 00:36:38.690
Tell her you're not?

00:36:38.690 --> 00:36:40.080
That's ridiculous.

00:36:40.080 --> 00:36:41.800
I have to be able
to talk about this.

00:36:41.800 --> 00:36:43.620
And so I had to
take a deep breath

00:36:43.620 --> 00:36:46.164
and face my own discomfort.

00:36:46.164 --> 00:36:48.580
I tell this story because when
I was researching the book,

00:36:48.580 --> 00:36:50.038
one of the things
that I learned is

00:36:50.038 --> 00:36:52.306
that there's been
all this psychology

00:36:52.306 --> 00:36:53.680
and psychological
research that's

00:36:53.680 --> 00:36:57.310
been done about conversations
around race with children.

00:36:57.310 --> 00:36:59.330
And it turns out-- and
so much of white America,

00:36:59.330 --> 00:37:01.050
we want to be colorblind, right?

00:37:01.050 --> 00:37:02.600
We want to see
everyone as the same.

00:37:02.600 --> 00:37:04.808
And that is a big theme in
this election, by the way.

00:37:04.808 --> 00:37:08.270
If you watch five minutes
of conservative news,

00:37:08.270 --> 00:37:09.960
if you watch Fox
for five minutes,

00:37:09.960 --> 00:37:12.080
you will hear guest
after guest after guest

00:37:12.080 --> 00:37:15.410
challenge the assumption that
there is racism in the country,

00:37:15.410 --> 00:37:17.300
challenge the
assumption that any

00:37:17.300 --> 00:37:20.495
of the big issues that
we're facing are about race.

00:37:20.495 --> 00:37:21.870
And you've got to
listen to that,

00:37:21.870 --> 00:37:24.100
because it's actually
a very significant part

00:37:24.100 --> 00:37:25.362
of the American perspective.

00:37:25.362 --> 00:37:27.320
And if we deny it, we're
missing a whole thing.

00:37:27.320 --> 00:37:28.770
But here's the thing about it.

00:37:28.770 --> 00:37:31.110
So even the most
well-intentioned

00:37:31.110 --> 00:37:33.440
among us, who think
that by not talking

00:37:33.440 --> 00:37:38.240
about race with our kids we
are raving colorblind children.

00:37:38.240 --> 00:37:40.090
Well, it turns out that,
psychologically, it

00:37:40.090 --> 00:37:44.920
has the opposite effect, that
in the absence of conversation,

00:37:44.920 --> 00:37:48.340
in the absence of information,
our children actually

00:37:48.340 --> 00:37:51.350
draw a negative conclusion.

00:37:51.350 --> 00:37:55.230
The very thing that so many
white Americans do to try to be

00:37:55.230 --> 00:37:57.590
good citizens-- "we don't
need to talk about that,

00:37:57.590 --> 00:38:00.704
because we're all the same"--
it's exactly the wrong choice.

00:38:00.704 --> 00:38:02.120
Because it's
actually reinforcing.

00:38:02.120 --> 00:38:04.400
Our kids assume that when
we're not talking about it,

00:38:04.400 --> 00:38:06.050
it's because there's
something wrong or bad

00:38:06.050 --> 00:38:07.182
that we're uncomfortable with.

00:38:07.182 --> 00:38:09.020
ALYSIA REINER: I want
to piggyback on that.

00:38:09.020 --> 00:38:09.650
LAUREN LEADER CHIVEE:
And then in the media,

00:38:09.650 --> 00:38:10.660
we're not talking
about it either.

00:38:10.660 --> 00:38:11.700
So where are they
going to get it?

00:38:11.700 --> 00:38:12.658
ALYSIA REINER: Correct.

00:38:12.658 --> 00:38:18.920
And I feel like it's so much
better and easier with kids,

00:38:18.920 --> 00:38:20.980
because they're
so much more open.

00:38:20.980 --> 00:38:24.110
When you guys have
workshops on diversity,

00:38:24.110 --> 00:38:28.000
it feels a little
forced sometimes.

00:38:28.000 --> 00:38:34.940
And I think with kids, at our
school, sincec first grade,

00:38:34.940 --> 00:38:38.210
she's had racial justice
and advocacy classes,

00:38:38.210 --> 00:38:40.140
in the first grade.

00:38:40.140 --> 00:38:47.330
And my favorite part
is they talk regularly.

00:38:47.330 --> 00:38:51.040
There are four different
kinds-- not kinds of people.

00:38:51.040 --> 00:38:52.550
They would hate me saying that.

00:38:52.550 --> 00:38:55.610
There are four
different categories

00:38:55.610 --> 00:38:58.280
of human in anything situation.

00:38:58.280 --> 00:39:02.150
So in any situation where
there is a conflict,

00:39:02.150 --> 00:39:06.000
there's the mistake-maker,
the target, the bystander,

00:39:06.000 --> 00:39:07.660
and the ally.

00:39:07.660 --> 00:39:11.390
What I love about
that breakdown is

00:39:11.390 --> 00:39:16.520
that the mistake-maker
and the bystander

00:39:16.520 --> 00:39:21.350
are almost neck and neck as
mistake-makers, that if you

00:39:21.350 --> 00:39:25.370
are a bystander, that's not OK.

00:39:25.370 --> 00:39:28.000
And I love that my daughter
goes to a school that

00:39:28.000 --> 00:39:31.110
teaches it is not OK
to be a bystander,

00:39:31.110 --> 00:39:34.130
that it is your
job to be an ally.

00:39:34.130 --> 00:39:35.870
That is your job in life.

00:39:35.870 --> 00:39:39.370
And that's that
unconscious bias.

00:39:39.370 --> 00:39:44.705
How do we untrain ourselves and
how do we train our children?

00:39:44.705 --> 00:39:46.580
LAUREN LEADER CHIVEE:
So I want to open it up

00:39:46.580 --> 00:39:47.840
to a conversation in the room.

00:39:47.840 --> 00:39:50.654
There's lots of better
perspectives than ours.

00:39:50.654 --> 00:39:52.490
AUDIENCE: Hi, wanted
talk about something

00:39:52.490 --> 00:39:54.956
