I have nothing in
common with somebody

00:47:12.930 --> 00:47:17.230
who is that hateful about
entire groups of people.

00:47:17.230 --> 00:47:20.139
I cannot relate to that, and I
wish I was a better person than

00:47:20.139 --> 00:47:21.430
I'd be willing to take that on.

00:47:21.430 --> 00:47:22.635
I can't.

00:47:22.635 --> 00:47:25.910
But the truth is the vast
majority of Americans

00:47:25.910 --> 00:47:28.770
are nowhere near those
polar ends of the scale.

00:47:28.770 --> 00:47:33.070
And it is the dystopian
world of the current media

00:47:33.070 --> 00:47:35.580
cycle that makes us
think that is the case.

00:47:35.580 --> 00:47:38.840
And it means that we're left
likely to have some very

00:47:38.840 --> 00:47:40.610
important conversations.

00:47:40.610 --> 00:47:44.030
And there are a lot of common
bonds between people who

00:47:44.030 --> 00:47:45.550
have different political views.

00:47:45.550 --> 00:47:47.390
And if we can't have
those conversations,

00:47:47.390 --> 00:47:50.280
if we're so
uncomfortable with them,

00:47:50.280 --> 00:47:53.160
it's another piece
of this equation,

00:47:53.160 --> 00:47:57.207
that we have to be able to do
that and find common ground

00:47:57.207 --> 00:47:58.290
and to respect each other.

00:47:58.290 --> 00:48:00.290
And look, I think that
is in some ways happening

00:48:00.290 --> 00:48:01.680
in this election.

00:48:01.680 --> 00:48:03.590
The Republicans
who have subscribed

00:48:03.590 --> 00:48:08.182
to Never-Trump specifically
because of the racism

00:48:08.182 --> 00:48:12.490
and the misogyny that has
been such a critical part

00:48:12.490 --> 00:48:13.635
of this campaign.

00:48:13.635 --> 00:48:15.510
I may not agree with
them on a lot of things,

00:48:15.510 --> 00:48:17.870
but I thoroughly agree
with them on that.

00:48:17.870 --> 00:48:21.250
So my only point
is that I think we

00:48:21.250 --> 00:48:25.170
have to see those conversations
across the political divide

00:48:25.170 --> 00:48:29.150
as still part of
the same equation.

00:48:29.150 --> 00:48:32.510
It's hard and it's uncomfortable
and we all hate it,

00:48:32.510 --> 00:48:34.799
because of the challenge.

00:48:34.799 --> 00:48:36.090
I don't like watching Fox News.

00:48:36.090 --> 00:48:39.730
It makes me mad because I
don't agree, but I do it.

00:48:39.730 --> 00:48:41.250
And I go on the
show and I do it,

00:48:41.250 --> 00:48:44.280
because I don't know how I
understand the country if I'm

00:48:44.280 --> 00:48:46.270
totally tuning it
out, just as I would

00:48:46.270 --> 00:48:52.100
want them, more conservatives,
watching MSNBC, right?

00:48:52.100 --> 00:48:53.950
So I mean, these are
some of these big,

00:48:53.950 --> 00:48:58.220
hard things that we're
going to have to face,

00:48:58.220 --> 00:49:00.250
unless we're OK with
where we are today,

00:49:00.250 --> 00:49:02.190
which I think most of
us probably aren't.

00:49:02.190 --> 00:49:03.815
So it's in no way
meant as a criticism,

00:49:03.815 --> 00:49:06.760
and I think we're
all doing our best

00:49:06.760 --> 00:49:10.900
to try to contribute
to a better discourse,

00:49:10.900 --> 00:49:13.426
but I had just to say
something about that.

00:49:13.426 --> 00:49:17.490
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I
more adding on that.

00:49:17.490 --> 00:49:20.884
I thought I'll give you
an easier question there.

00:49:20.884 --> 00:49:27.210
I live in Queens, which
is I guess the most

00:49:27.210 --> 00:49:29.025
diverse neighborhood now.

00:49:29.025 --> 00:49:29.900
ALYSIA REINER: It is.

00:49:29.900 --> 00:49:30.390
It's true.

00:49:30.390 --> 00:49:30.880
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:49:30.880 --> 00:49:32.171
AUDIENCE: So I'm lucky on that.

00:49:32.171 --> 00:49:35.462
However, when I was growing
up, I grew in India,

00:49:35.462 --> 00:49:39.020
where I had my own
feelings about that,

00:49:39.020 --> 00:49:44.702
that before the '90s, I would
go into each of the neighbors'

00:49:44.702 --> 00:49:47.285
homes, whether they were Hindus
or Muslims, it doesn't matter.

00:49:47.285 --> 00:49:51.844
I would go into a mosque
right away without much issue.

00:49:51.844 --> 00:49:53.510
Suddenly, I realized
something happened.

00:49:53.510 --> 00:49:54.801
Everybody was talking about it.

00:49:54.801 --> 00:49:56.210
It was like, '91, '92.

00:49:56.210 --> 00:49:59.020
And then we stopped going
to each other's houses

00:49:59.020 --> 00:50:01.830
unless they were
the same religion.

00:50:01.830 --> 00:50:05.194
We stopped going across
the mosques and temples.

00:50:05.194 --> 00:50:07.360
Something happened, and I
realized, "oh, some mosque

00:50:07.360 --> 00:50:10.740
was demolished in
'91." [INAUDIBLE]

00:50:10.740 --> 00:50:13.400
And that segregation,
to my surprise

00:50:13.400 --> 00:50:15.800
when I went back a couple of
years ago, is still there.

00:50:15.800 --> 00:50:16.925
LAUREN LEADER CHIVEE: Yeah.

00:50:16.925 --> 00:50:19.880
AUDIENCE: So now, actually I
thought somehow in my mind,

00:50:19.880 --> 00:50:20.910
"oh, that's temporary.

00:50:20.910 --> 00:50:22.540
It will go away."

00:50:22.540 --> 00:50:25.040
No, across a generation,
it's still there.

00:50:25.040 --> 00:50:28.640
So segregations, when they
happen, they just stay.

00:50:28.640 --> 00:50:31.044
That's what my take is, unless
you do something about it.

00:50:31.044 --> 00:50:32.210
LAUREN LEADER CHIVEE: Right.

00:50:32.210 --> 00:50:32.869
It doesn't.

00:50:32.869 --> 00:50:34.160
And people ask us all the time.

00:50:34.160 --> 00:50:35.070
I get asked all the time.

00:50:35.070 --> 00:50:35.780
As someone who
works on this stuff,

00:50:35.780 --> 00:50:36.821
I get asked all the time.

00:50:36.821 --> 00:50:40.080
Do you think that
the rise of Gen Y,

00:50:40.080 --> 00:50:42.940
Gen Y in the United States, as
the most of diverse generation

00:50:42.940 --> 00:50:45.880
in history, the most well
educated generation in history,

00:50:45.880 --> 00:50:49.190
that's just going
to change things?

00:50:49.190 --> 00:50:52.470
I don't know that it
does, automatically.

00:50:52.470 --> 00:50:54.810
I actually think
it does take work.

00:50:54.810 --> 00:50:57.250
And I'm glad you mentioned
the religious piece.

00:50:57.250 --> 00:50:59.360
I wrote a little bit
about that, but that's

00:50:59.360 --> 00:51:02.050
another place where we
make choices every day

00:51:02.050 --> 00:51:04.530
about the kind of churches that
we go to and whether or not

00:51:04.530 --> 00:51:09.850
we're choosing churches and
synagogues or mosques that are

00:51:09.850 --> 00:51:12.530
welcoming and inclusive or not.

00:51:12.530 --> 00:51:16.010
I think in the Christian
community especially,

00:51:16.010 --> 00:51:21.255
there's so many different--
there's 1,000 flavors.

00:51:21.255 --> 00:51:23.380
There's that question of
choosing churches that are

00:51:23.380 --> 00:51:24.962
more diverse or less diverse.

00:51:24.962 --> 00:51:26.920
And it's another way that
we make those choices

00:51:26.920 --> 00:51:30.948
for our families and
create conversation or not.

00:51:30.948 --> 00:51:32.896
but these are very
closely held beliefs,

00:51:32.896 --> 00:51:34.270
and people get
very uncomfortable

00:51:34.270 --> 00:51:37.860
when their closely held beliefs
are in anyway challenged,

00:51:37.860 --> 00:51:39.909
but that's the
plurality of our nation.

00:51:39.909 --> 00:51:40.825
How do we not do that?

00:51:43.990 --> 00:51:46.175
I mean, in the film, there's
been so much-- anyway,

00:51:46.175 --> 00:51:46.570
what were you doing to say?

00:51:46.570 --> 00:51:48.120
ALYSIA REINER: I was
just going to say--

00:51:48.120 --> 00:51:49.694
LAUREN LEADER CHIVEE: Sorry,
did you have something else?

00:51:49.694 --> 00:51:50.186
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I had
a continued question.

00:51:50.186 --> 00:51:51.394
LAUREN LEADER CHIVEE: Please.

00:51:51.394 --> 00:51:53.870
AUDIENCE: So on that round,
I think with four year olds,

00:51:53.870 --> 00:51:55.161
we'd have an easier shot there.

00:51:55.161 --> 00:52:00.600
Because they can keep three
things in their mind, right?

00:52:00.600 --> 00:52:05.000
If they decide hey, if they
talk to everybody and chat

00:52:05.000 --> 00:52:07.057
with everybody, then
that's the best start.

00:52:07.057 --> 00:52:08.140
So I have a four year old.

00:52:08.140 --> 00:52:10.860
And he asks me sometimes
that he wants to be a girl,

00:52:10.860 --> 00:52:12.720
or he wants to be this,
he wants to be that.

00:52:12.720 --> 00:52:13.386
I say, "oh yeah.

00:52:13.386 --> 00:52:14.140
You can choose.

00:52:14.140 --> 00:52:15.410
The world has come to this.

00:52:15.410 --> 00:52:18.360
You can be whatever you
want later on, but not now.

00:52:18.360 --> 00:52:21.170
Let's figure out
what you want to be."

00:52:21.170 --> 00:52:24.250
So if he asked me how is
meeting different people

00:52:24.250 --> 00:52:26.560
or different kinds
of people useful,

00:52:26.560 --> 00:52:28.990
how is diversity
useful to him, and you

00:52:28.990 --> 00:52:31.490
have to say only three things,
because it's a four year old.

00:52:31.490 --> 00:52:34.240
They can't remember
more than three.

00:52:34.240 --> 00:52:35.370
What would you say?

00:52:35.370 --> 00:52:37.340
Why would diversity
be useful to you

00:52:37.340 --> 00:52:38.737
growing up or later in life?

00:52:38.737 --> 00:52:40.862
ALYSIA REINER: To a four
year old or to a grown up?

00:52:40.862 --> 00:52:42.000
LAUREN LEADER CHIVEE:
To a four year old.

00:52:42.000 --> 00:52:42.530
You're saying to
a four year old.

00:52:42.530 --> 00:52:43.071
I don't know.

00:52:43.071 --> 00:52:45.128
What did you say?

00:52:45.128 --> 00:52:46.336
AUDIENCE: I'm still thinking.

00:52:46.336 --> 00:52:48.127
LAUREN LEADER CHIVEE:
You're still looking?

00:52:48.127 --> 00:52:49.990
You're still thinking
about the answer.

00:52:49.990 --> 00:52:51.620
You do [INAUDIBLE]
four year olds.

00:52:51.620 --> 00:52:53.800
What would yours be?

00:52:53.800 --> 00:52:55.540
I love that question.

00:52:55.540 --> 00:52:57.660
ALYSIA REINER: So if my
four year old asked me--

00:52:57.660 --> 00:52:58.660
I just want to be clear.

00:52:58.660 --> 00:53:03.725
If my four year old asked me
why I have diversity important?

00:53:03.725 --> 00:53:05.600
AUDIENCE: Yeah, or useful
to them growing up.

00:53:05.600 --> 00:53:07.801
ALYSIA REINER: Yeah,
useful to them growing up.

00:53:07.801 --> 00:53:10.830
AUDIENCE: Why would [INAUDIBLE]
"Crossing the Thinnest Line"

00:53:10.830 --> 00:53:11.496
would be useful.

00:53:15.039 --> 00:53:16.580
ALYSIA REINER: That
my honest answer,

00:53:16.580 --> 00:53:18.855
if she said that right
now-- I'm an actress,

00:53:18.855 --> 00:53:21.610
so I have to imagine that
I'm doing it right now.

00:53:21.610 --> 00:53:24.680
LAUREN LEADER CHIVEE: Would
you like me to play Liz?

00:53:24.680 --> 00:53:27.170
ALYSIA REINER: No,
you're too pretty.

00:53:27.170 --> 00:53:36.290
No, I would say, "baby,
don't you know"--

00:53:36.290 --> 00:53:37.345
no, I wouldn't say that.

00:53:37.345 --> 00:53:38.270
LAUREN LEADER CHIVEE: Do you
need more time to prepare?

00:53:38.270 --> 00:53:39.440
ALYSIA REINER: Yeah, I do.

00:53:39.440 --> 00:53:44.910
But I would really say
the more experience

00:53:44.910 --> 00:53:52.260
we have of life, the more
we know of the more people

00:53:52.260 --> 00:53:57.570
and the more experiences,
the more compassion we have,

00:53:57.570 --> 00:53:58.494
the more we can serve.

00:53:58.494 --> 00:54:00.410
LAUREN LEADER CHIVEE:
Yeah, that's a good one.

00:54:00.410 --> 00:54:02.850
ALYSIA REINER: And then I
would give a concrete example.

00:54:02.850 --> 00:54:04.820
Because that's all--

00:54:04.820 --> 00:54:05.680
[MUMBLING]

00:54:06.970 --> 00:54:09.850
So what I'm thinking
about right now

00:54:09.850 --> 00:54:13.250
is what's the concrete example?

00:54:13.250 --> 00:54:20.180
And I would probably get
a book about two kids.

00:54:20.180 --> 00:54:21.630
And I'm sure they have this.

00:54:21.630 --> 00:54:23.250
Someone's written
this beautiful book

00:54:23.250 --> 00:54:26.040
about you walk a
mile in my shoes

00:54:26.040 --> 00:54:27.970
and I walk a mile in yours.

00:54:27.970 --> 00:54:32.910
And how do we then appreciate
each other's lives?

00:54:32.910 --> 00:54:35.900
And it really is what
Lauren was talking

00:54:35.900 --> 00:54:40.170
about-- make friends with
that super conservative guy

00:54:40.170 --> 00:54:41.550
that you don't understand.

00:54:41.550 --> 00:54:45.450
Because if you understand
him, in that process,

00:54:45.450 --> 00:54:46.530
he'll understand you.

00:54:46.530 --> 00:54:49.710
I was actually
thinking I dare anyone

00:54:49.710 --> 00:54:50.880
to come make this with me.

00:54:50.880 --> 00:54:54.090
I want to make a little
"Saturday Night Live" sketch

00:54:54.090 --> 00:55:01.090
of "befriend your
conservative white male."

00:55:01.090 --> 00:55:04.710
Because for me, that's
really hard sometimes.

00:55:04.710 --> 00:55:08.260
Because their
opinions are so not

00:55:08.260 --> 00:55:13.990
mine and I have my own
unconscious bias about that.

00:55:13.990 --> 00:55:18.620
And how do we create
more situations

00:55:18.620 --> 00:55:20.440
where we're in
rooms together where

00:55:20.440 --> 00:55:25.200
we're understanding and then can
have compassion for each other.

00:55:25.200 --> 00:55:26.899
I'll say my little
wrap-up about--

00:55:26.899 --> 00:55:28.440
LAUREN LEADER CHIVEE:
We're overtime.

00:55:28.440 --> 00:55:31.840
ALYSIA REINER: Sorry,
about what I talk about.

00:55:31.840 --> 00:55:35.020
And this is a direct
quote from Effie Brown,

00:55:35.020 --> 00:55:37.360
who's an amazing producer.

00:55:37.360 --> 00:55:39.140
And she talks about
the three things

00:55:39.140 --> 00:55:42.810
you can do to change things
for women are hire, mentor,

00:55:42.810 --> 00:55:44.540
and invest.

00:55:44.540 --> 00:55:50.240
So hire more women,
invest in women.

00:55:50.240 --> 00:55:53.869
And if you can't do
either of those, mentor.

00:55:53.869 --> 00:55:55.660
LAUREN LEADER CHIVEE:
So we're out of time.

00:55:55.660 --> 00:55:57.576
I don't have all the
answers, and I definitely

00:55:57.576 --> 00:56:00.300
didn't write the book because
I had all the answers.

00:56:00.300 --> 00:56:02.460
I tried to ask some
questions that I hope

00:56:02.460 --> 00:56:03.710
we'll all keep thinking about.

00:56:03.710 --> 00:56:06.160
And I would really love for
you to buy the book before you

00:56:06.160 --> 00:56:07.970
leave, but I would
especially love

00:56:07.970 --> 00:56:10.290
for you to continue
this conversation

00:56:10.290 --> 00:56:13.120
through social channels and
with your friends and online.

00:56:13.120 --> 00:56:16.430
We need this conversation now
maybe more than ever before,

00:56:16.430 --> 00:56:18.110
certainly in our lifetime.

00:56:18.110 --> 00:56:20.930
And we need it thoughtfully
and inclusively,

00:56:20.930 --> 00:56:23.660
and we need to bring
her best to it.

00:56:23.660 --> 00:56:26.160
Because these are some of the
most complicated and difficult

00:56:26.160 --> 00:56:27.560
challenges of our time.

00:56:27.560 --> 00:56:30.842
And I think it takes all
of us working towards it,

00:56:30.842 --> 00:56:32.800
working towards the
solution to make it better.

00:56:32.800 --> 00:56:36.030
So thank you so much to Karen
and to everyone at Google.

00:56:36.030 --> 00:56:37.510
Thank you for having us.

00:56:37.510 --> 00:56:38.610
KAREN: Thank you.

00:56:38.610 --> 00:56:41.970
[APPLAUSE]

